prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: Band 7 observations of z~4 LBGs
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: This science goal is to obtain band 7 measurements of 71 bright z~4 LBGs. This will allow us to estimate the IR luminosities and thus constrain the obscured star formation in our sample.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: Continuum observations requested. Band 7 is selected as it produces the optimum S/N distribution based on our predictions.
The requested angular resolution is chosen to ensure that the targets will be unresolved by ALMA data (confirmed by the sizes measured in HST imaging), maximising the S/N for detections.

Our predictions for the ALMA fluxes of each individual source are based on observations of their UV luminosity and continuum slope.
The observed UV continuum slope (beta) is theoretically expected and empirically demonstrated [using stacking at z~1.5-3] (e.g. Heinis+2013; Heinis+2014; Coppin+2015) to correlate with the observed ratio of the total IR to UV luminosity and thus dust attenuation.
Instead of relying on previous observations we develop a theoretical framework from which we can obtain predictions for the IRX-beta relationship. Within this framework we can vary any of the parameters.
The first step in this framework is to specify an intrinsic SED. We do this using the PEGASE.2 stellar population synthesis model and assume 100 Myr previous constant star formation, Z=0.008 stellar metallicity, and an escape fraction of 0.0. This intrinsic SED is shown in Fig. 3.
We then include dust by assuming a choice of E(B-V) (or A_V) and dust curve(s). Using an energy balance approach we can then estimate the IR luminosity and by asusming an IR template [in our case we assume a greybody+NIR power-law (Casey+2013) with T=30K, emisivity=1.5, and alpha=2.0] we can then predict the rest-frame IR SED and how it changes with E(B-V), A_V, or beta. An example SED created using this procedure is shown in Fig. 3.
From this "total" SED we can derive a relationship between the observed UV continuum slope and the ratio of the rest-frame UV flux (i.e. the observed NIR flux) and the expected observed ALMA flux (see Fig. 4). For each individual source, we can then predict its expected ALMA flux.
This relationship is sensitive to the entire range of assumptions, however it is particularly sensitive to the choice of dust curve. Assuming an SMC-like curve yields rest-frame IR fluxes (for a given UV continuum slope and flux) which are typically ~4-5 lower than assuming a Calzetti+2000 curve.
Assuming a Calzetti+2000 curve (favoured by the stacking results at z~3) we obtain a median S/N for the sample of ~14.5. If instead we assume an SMC-like curve (Pei+92) the median S/N is ~4. The full signal-to-noise distribution is shown in Fig. 4.
Our choice of sensitivity is motivated by the desire to robustly characterise the IRX-\beta relation independent of the choice of dust curve and while some objects are expected to be detected at only low-S/N our predictions show that it is still possible to robustly characterise the IRX-beta relationship.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: The study of rest-frame UV selected Lyman-break galaxies (LBGs) now allows us to probe star formation activity in the Universe to z~10, only 500 million years after the big bang. However, the UV traces star formation unobscured by dust and thus provides only a lower limit on the star formation activity in these galaxies and thus the Universe. To complete the census of star formation at high-redshift we propose a comprehensive survey of z~4 LBGs with ALMA. Specifically, we propose to target a sample of 71 z~4 LBGs with ALMA to obtain measurements of the rest-frame IR continuum at ~200um. From these observations we will be able to estimate the total IR luminosities and thus the amount of obscured star formation in these systems. This representative sample, which probes a range of UV continuum slopes, will allow us to calibrate the IRX-beta relationship allowing us to estimate the obscured star formation activity in faint systems otherwise inaccessible to ALMA.
prp:ObsProposal.prp:scientificCategoryString: Cosmology and the High Redshift Universe
